# Rust / Cargo via Docker

This project does **not** have Cargo installed on the host. All Cargo-related commands must be run inside the Docker image **scorelib-builder:latest**.

## Rule

- **Never** run `cargo` directly (e.g. `cargo build`, `cargo test`, `cargo run`). Cargo is not installed on the laptop.
- **Always** run Cargo via Docker using the image **scorelib-builder:latest**.

## Command pattern

From the **project root** (workspace root), run:

```bash
docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)":/workspace -w /workspace scorelib-builder:latest cargo <command> [args]
```

Examples:

- Build: `docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)":/workspace -w /workspace scorelib-builder:latest cargo build`
- Test: `docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)":/workspace -w /workspace scorelib-builder:latest cargo test`
- Run: `docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)":/workspace -w /workspace scorelib-builder:latest cargo run`
- Check: `docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)":/workspace -w /workspace scorelib-builder:latest cargo check`
- Clippy: `docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)":/workspace -w /workspace scorelib-builder:latest cargo clippy`
- Fmt: `docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)":/workspace -w /workspace scorelib-builder:latest cargo fmt`

## Notes

- Ensure the shell is in the project root before running (e.g. `cd /Users/tli/hl/src/github.com/websocket` or the workspace path).
- For long-running commands (e.g. `cargo run`), use the same pattern; add `-p 8080:8080` (or the app port) to `docker run` if the app listens on a port and you need to reach it from the host.
- When running tests or builds that need network (e.g. fetching crates), use `docker run` with `--network host` or ensure the image can reach the internet by default.
